The '''2010 G-20 Toronto summit''' was the [[List of G-20 summits|fourth meeting]] of the [[G-20 major economies|G-20]] [[Head of government|heads of government]], in discussion of the [[global financial system]] and the [[world economy]], which took place at the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, during June 26<U+2013>27, 2010. The summit's priorities included evaluating the progress of financial reform, developing sustainable stimulus measures,<ref>http://www.economicsummits.info/2010/03/harpers-comments-to-the-sherpas-document/</ref> debating [[bank tax|global bank tax]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/background-summit-issues/article1547024/ |title=Background: Summit Issues |publisher=Globe and Mail |date=April 28, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and promoting [[open market]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=3209 |title=Prime Minister of Canada: Statement by the Prime Minister of Canada |publisher=Pm.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> Alongside the twenty-one representatives of the G-20 major economies, leaders of six invited nations, and eight additional [[intergovernmental organization]]s also took part in the summit.

Prior to the summit, [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian prime minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] announced that the theme of the Toronto summit would be "recovery and new beginnings," referring to an anticipated [[economic stimulus]] from the impact of the [[Late-2000s recession|ongoing world recession]].<ref>http://www.economicsummits.info/2010/03/harpers-comments-to-the-sherpas-document/</ref> The summit was initially proposed to be held in the town of [[Huntsville, Ontario]], where the immediately preceding [[36th G8 summit]] was set to be held. The town was later deemed insufficient to provide hospitality for the large number of G-20 delegates and journalists, thus the summit was later finalized to take place in Toronto.<ref name=washingtonexaminer1>{{cite web|author=6:26 EDT |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/world/canada-says-spending-nearly-1-billion-on-security-for-g-8-and-g-20-summits-is-worth-it-95107194.html |title=Canada says spending nearly {{Nowrap|$1 billion}} on security for G8 and G-20 summits is worth it |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=2010-05-28 |accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref>

An [[Integrated Security Unit]], consisting of police officers from different regional departments, was formed to provide security during the summit in [[Downtown Toronto]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Toronto Police Service |url=http://www.torontopolice.on.ca/g20/ |title=Toronto Police Service :: To Serve and Protect |publisher=Torontopolice.on.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> where the venue was located. The event was part of the largest and most expensive security operation in [[History of Canada|Canadian history]]. The total cost for preparations,<ref>{{cite web|author=Alcoba, Natalie|url=http://network.nationalpost.com/NP/blogs/toronto/archive/2010/02/22/g8-g20-gearing-up-for-the-biggest-security-event-in-canadian-history.aspx#ixzz0gXPVjsqt |title=G8/G20: Gearing up for the biggest security event in Canadian history|publisher=Posted Toronto |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> including security, infrastructure, and hospitality, was determined to be approximately [[Canadian dollar|C$]]858 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/toronto/story/2010/11/05/g20-costs-tabled.html |title=CBC News <U+2013> Toronto <U+2013> G8/G20 costs top $857M |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2010-11-05 |accessdate=2010-11-05}}</ref>

==Agenda==
Many leaders of the [[G-20 major economies|G-20]] were divided among different issues that they wanted to discuss at the summit.<ref>Wolverson, Roya. [http://www.cfr.org/publication/22542/g20s_twenty_agendas.html?breadcrumb=%2Fpublication%2Fby_type%2Fbackgrounder "The G20's Twenty Agendas,"] ''Council on Foreign Relations'' (US). June 24, 2010, retrieved 2011-04-06</ref> The prime focus of the summit discussions was the recovery from the ongoing [[Late-2000s recession|global recession]] and the [[2010 European sovereign debt crisis|European debt crisis]]. Summit leaders were divided over which strategies would be best for tackling these problems. The [[European Union]] emphasized the need to cut their deficits by focusing on [[austerity]] measures.  In contrast, the [[United States]] emphasized the importance of maintaining [[economic stimulus]] spending in order to encourage growth.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/2010/06/2010627114252622620.html "Recession recovery tops G20 agenda,"] ''Al Jazeera'' (Qatar). June 28, 2010, retrieved 2011-04-06</ref> In summit discussions, the countries of the European Union explained projected reductions in spending and balanced budgets.  A different approach was projected by the [[People's Republic of China|China]], India, and the United States, arguing in favor of increased stimulus funding to mitigate the effects of recession. Among the specifics proposed by the European Union were a global [[bank tax]] and a [[Robin Hood tax]], but these plans were opposed by the United States and [[Canada]].<ref>Davies, Rhodri. [http://english.aljazeera.net/focus/2010/06/201062571713780493.html "G20:Battles within and outside,"] ''Al Jazeera'' (Qatar). June 28, 2010, retrieved 2011-04-06.</ref> Other topics of concern were [[international development]] and continuing [[international aid]] to [[Africa]] and other developing nations.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/insidestory/2010/06/2010624125511683950.html "Forgotten goals,"] ''Al Jazeera'' (Qatar). June 28, 2010, retrieved 2011-04-06.</ref>  Criticism of [[Israel]]'s [[Blockade of the Gaza Strip (2007<U+2013>present)|Gaza strip blockade]] and criticism of the nuclear programs of [[North Korea]] was expressed. Issues of corruption and security in [[Afghanistan]] was raised by the United States.

== Preparations ==
{{Main|2010 G-20 Toronto summit preparations}}
=== Security ===
[[File:Fences Are Up Toronto 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Security fencing erected along the middle of Wellington Street]]
Security officials began preparing for summit security in Toronto around mid-February 2010.<ref>[http://www.g8-g20isu.ca/g20/about-apropos-eng.htm  Integrated Security Unit (ISU)]: [http://www.g8-g20isu.ca/g20/news-nouvelles/10-02-19-eng.htm  "Metro Toronto Convention Centre will be the official venue of the G20 Summit in Toronto in June,"] February 19, 2010.</ref> General policing and patrolling was provided by the [[Toronto Police Service]], the [[Ontario Provincial Police]], the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], and the [[Canadian Forces]], while the [[Peel Regional Police]] aided in policing at [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] in [[Mississauga]] during the arrivals of delegates. The five departments formed an [[Integrated Security Unit]] (ISU), similar to the ISU created during the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]]. Additional officers were deployed from [[York Regional Police]], [[Halton Regional Police Service]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/22/peter-kuitenbrouwer-downtown-doesnt-feel-like-home-during-g20/ |title=Peter Kuitenbrouwer: Downtown doesn<U+2019>t feel like home during G20 &#124; Posted Toronto &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2010-06-29}}</ref> [[Barrie Police Service]], [[Waterloo Regional Police Service]], [[Niagara Regional Police Service]], [[Hamilton Police Service]], [[Ottawa Police Service]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news/article/839309--protesters-gather-at-allan-gardens-to-oppose-g20-summit |title=Protesters gather at Allan Gardens to oppose G20 Summit |publisher=InsideToronto Article |date=2010-06-25 |accessdate=2010-06-29}}</ref> and [[Service de police de la Ville de Montr<U+00E9>al]]. [[Calgary Police Service]] supplied 150 volunteer police officers a week before the summit.<ref>{{cite web|author=Calgary Herald June 14, 2010 |url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/news/Calgary+police+head+Toronto+massive+security+effort/3150428/story.html |title=Calgary police head to Toronto for massive G20 security effort |publisher=Calgaryherald.com |date=2010-06-14 |accessdate=2010-06-22}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

According to an early estimate by the ''[[Globe and Mail]]'', 10,000 uniformed police officers, 1,000 security guards, and several Canadian military forces were to be deployed during the summit.<ref name=mondaq1>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondaq.com/canada/article.asp?articleid=99928 |title=Canada, Labour and Employment, Toronto G8 and G20 Summits <U+2013> Employer Planning Issues <U+2013> Bennett Jones LLP <U+2013> 06/05/2010, Health & Safety |publisher=Mondaq.com |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> The [[North American Aerospace Defense Command]] (NORAD) conducted [[Amalgam Virgo]] exercises on May 6 and 7 across the [[Greater Toronto Area]] using [[CF-18 Hornet]] jets, [[CH-124 Sea King]]s, and [[CH-146 Griffon]] helicopters at low altitudes.<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/its-a-bird-its-a-plane-its-a-terrifying-display-of-military-might/article1558886/ |title=It's a bird, it's a plane, it's a terrifying display of military might |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=2010-05-06 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> The total cost for security at both the G8 and the G-20 summits was determined to be {{Nowrap|$1 billion<!--THIS IS ONLY THE ESTIMATE THAT WAS GIVEN BEFORE THE SUMMIT. DO NOT CHANGE TO THE ACTUAL VALUE THAT WAS CALCULATED AFTER THE SUMMIT. SEE THE REFERENCE.-->}},<ref>{{cite news|author=Susan Delacourt Ottawa Bureau |url=http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/816123--what-can-1-billion-buy?bn=1 |title=G20 security tab: What else could $1B buy? |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-05-28 |accessdate=2010-06-20 | location=Toronto}}</ref> paid entirely by the [[Government of Canada|federal Crown]]-[[Queen-in-Council|in-Council]], excluding the costs of any possible damage to local business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100528/g8-g20-costs-page-100528/20100528/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> Security chief defends high cost of G8-G20 summits <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref>

The ISU created a security perimeter, beginning with the outer boundary, specifically bordered by [[King Street (Toronto)|King Street]] to the north, [[Lake Shore Boulevard]] to the south, [[Yonge Street]] to the east, and [[Spadina Avenue]] to the west, where vehicles were to be restricted during the summit dates.<ref name="mondaq1"/> Residents who lived within the security zone were issued registration cards prior to the summit and other pedestrians who wished to enter the security zone were only able to do so at one of 38 checkpoints, where they were required to present two pieces of [[photo identification]] and provide reasoning for entry.<ref name=thestar2>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/825713--g20-survival-guide |title=G20 survival guide |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-18|accessdate=2010-06-20 | location=Toronto | first=Noor | last=Javed}}</ref> The area surrounding the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] itself was fenced and off limits to civilians and protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestar.blogs.com/g20/2010/05/details-of-g20-red-zone-announced.html |title= Details of G20 fence announced |publisher=TheStar.com |date=2010-05-28 |accessdate=2010-05-28}}</ref> The {{convert|3|m|ft|0|adj=on}} high fence, contracted to [[SNC-Lavalin]] by [[Public Works and Government Services Canada]] and installed by two [[Gormley, Ontario]]-based companies,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ormsby |first=Mary |url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/825908--fortress-toronto-secrets-of-the-fence |title=Fortress Toronto: Secrets of the fence |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-06-19 |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref> was built at a cost of {{Nowrap|$5.5-million}} and began erection on June 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2010/06/10/g20-torontos-controversial-security-fence-cost-5-5-million/ |title=G20: Toronto's controversial security fence cost $5.5-million &#124; Posted Toronto &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date=2010-06-10 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> Toronto Police Service installed 77 additional [[closed-circuit television]] security cameras in the area and purchased four [[Long Range Acoustic Device]]s which were to be in use exclusively during the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalnational.com/Toronto+Police+sound+security+tools/3108050/story.html |title=Police sound off on G20 security tools |publisher=Globalnational.com |date=2010-06-03 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> The ISU decided on also using [[water cannon]]s for [[riot control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/826245--police-add-water-cannon-to-g20-arsenal?bn=1 |title=Police add water cannon to G20 arsenal |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-21|accessdate=2010-06-24 | location=Toronto | first=Jesse | last=McLean}}</ref>

=== Infrastructure ===
A former film studio located on [[Eastern Avenue (Toronto)|Eastern Avenue]] was designated as a temporary detention centre for individuals arrested during the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/G20-Protest-100511/20100511/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> Protesters prepare for G20 demonstrations <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> Toronto Police Service announced that [[Trinity Bellwoods Park]] would be the designated protest area, but following opposition from local residents, police relocated the designated protest zone to the northern part of [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cp24.com/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100511/100511_protest/20100511/?hub=CP24Home |title=Police chief reconfirms that Queen's Park will be designated protest area during G20 <U+2013> CTV News, Shows and Sports <U+2013> Canadian Television |publisher=CP24 |date=2010-05-11 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> [[Canada Post]] declared that it would remove [[post box]]es in the security zone.<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/keep-those-cards-and-letters-coming/article1555282/ |title=Keep those cards and letters coming&nbsp;... |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=2010-05-04 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> [[Toronto Parking Authority]] removed some parking meters as well. Small trees along sidewalks around the convention centre were removed to prevent them from being used as weapons by protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.680news.com/news/local/article/67011--trees-could-be-removed-around-metro-convention-centre-for-summit |title=Trees could be removed around Metro Toronto Convention Centre for summit |publisher=680News |date=2010-06-16 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/pointofview/2010/06/g20-is-security-going-too-far.html |title=G20: Is security going too far? <U+2013> Point of View |publisher=Cbc.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> Other removed municipal property include 745 newspaper boxes, 200 public trash cans, 70 mailboxes, 29 bus shelters, and 5 public information boards.<ref>[http://nationalpostnews.files.wordpress.com/2010/06/g20-fortress-new.jpg "Fortress Toronto,"] ''National Post'' (Canada). June 2010.</ref>
[[File:G-20 Toronto June 2010 (1).jpg|thumb|left|Stores near [[King (TTC)|King Station]] apply wooden boards to prevent vandalism from protests]]

[[Big Five (banks)|Major banks headquartered in Downtown Toronto]], which happen to be the largest banks in Canada's banking industry, made plans to have employees work in alternate places outside of their downtown headquarters, such as at home or in other branches.<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/banks-make-plans-for-employees-to-work-off-site-during-g20/article1562639/ |title=Banks make plans for employees to work off-site during G20 |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date= |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> The [[Liquor Control Board of Ontario]] announced the closure of seven of [[liquor store]]s in Downtown during the summit as a precaution to looting.<ref name=toronto1>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100621/lcbo_shut_down_100621/20100621/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> Police ride herd as G20 protesters march the streets <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=2010-04-29 |accessdate=2010-06-22}}</ref> The [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]],<ref name=thestar2 /> [[CN Tower]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100519/G20-shuts-CNTower-100519/20100519/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> Amid G20 security concerns, CN Tower to be shut <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=2010-05-16 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> [[University of Toronto]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100524/G20-Shuts-UofT-100524/20100524/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> U of T to shut down during G20 Summit <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=2010-05-24 |accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref> [[Art Gallery of Ontario]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/arts/art-gallery-of-ontario-to-shutter-during-g20-summit/article1595077/ |title=Art Gallery of Ontario to shutter during G20 summit |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and the [[Ontario Legislative Building]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Rob Ferguson Queen's Park Bureau |url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/818484 |title=Legislature closing for G20 summit |publisher=thestar.com |date= 2010-06-03|accessdate=2010-06-04 | location=Toronto}}</ref> were also closed to public during the summit dates.

A three-game [[Major League Baseball]] series between the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] and the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], which was set to take place from June 25 to 27 at the [[Rogers Centre]], situated within the security zone, was relocated to [[Citizens Bank Park]] in [[Philadelphia]], after much discussion and amidst discontent from fans.<ref name=thestar1>{{cite news|author=Zwolinski, Mark|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/article/807716--g20-summit-scuppers-halladay-s-first-trip-to-toronto-as-a-phillie |title=G20 summit scuppers Halladay's first trip to Toronto as a Philly |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-05-11 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref><ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news|author=The Associated Press |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/12/sports/baseball/12bats.html?scp=1&sq=toronto&st=cse |title=Halladay's Return To Toronto Is Rerouted to Philadelphia |publisher=The New York Times |date= 2010-05-11 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref><ref name=theglobeandmail2>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/baseball/jays---phillies-series-moving-to-philadelphia/article1564925/ |title=Jays-Phillies series moving to Philadelphia |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date= |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100511&content_id=9963194&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jays' set vs. Phillies moved to Philadelphia|last=Bastian|first=Jordan|date=May 11, 2010|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=May 12, 2010}}</ref> [[Mirvish Productions]] cancelled production of their two musicals ''[[Rock of Ages (musical)#2010 Toronto|Rock of Ages]]'' and ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'' during the week of the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/travel/Mamma+derails+trains+Jays+plays/3117099/story.html |title=Mamma Mia! G20 derails trains, Jays and plays |publisher=Vancouversun.com |date=2010-06-05 |accessdate=2010-06-20}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Similarly, the [[Factory Theatre]] cancelled shows during the summit week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Theatre/2010/06/05/14274891.html |title=Canoe Jam! Theatre: G20 summit dims Toronto musicals |publisher=Jam.canoe.ca |date=2010-06-04 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref>

[[Ontario Highway 427|Highway 427]] and the [[Gardiner Expressway]], the route from [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] in [[Mississauga]] to the [[Metro Toronto Convention Centre]] in [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]], periodically closed down for motorcades, along with [[wireless signal jammer|jammed]] wireless reception along the two highways.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.680news.com/g20/article/64725--g8-g20-wireless-signal-blockers-unlikely-to-leave-cell-phone-users-in-a-jam |title=G8-G20 wireless signal blockers unlikely to leave cell phone users in a jam |publisher=680News |date=2010-06-09 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> Exits to [[Yonge Street]] and [[Bay Street]] on the Gardiner Expressway were closed during the summit dates.<ref name=thestar2 /> [[Toronto Transit Commission]] announced that [[List of Toronto subway and RT stations|subway stations]] near the convention centre would remain open and operational, despite some detoured [[Toronto Transit Commission buses|bus]] routes and the closure of [[Queens Quay (TTC)|Queens Quay Station]].<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/news/torontoandgta/2010/05/28/14179256.html G20 should cause only token disruption of TTC | Toronto & GTA | News | Toronto Sun<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Via Rail]] announced that it would not operate at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] during the summit dates,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100603/via-rail-g20-100603/20100603/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=CTV Toronto <U+2013> Via Rail to close at Union Station during G20 <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Toronto.ctv.ca |date=2009-07-26 |accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref> instead providing [[shuttle bus service]] from the [[Yorkdale Bus Terminal|Yorkdale]] and [[Scarborough Centre Bus Terminal|Scarborough Centre]] bus terminals to the [[Brampton GO Station|Brampton]] and [[Oshawa GO Station|Oshawa]] stations respectively.<ref name=thestar2 /> [[Nav Canada]] announced that it would place restrictions on the airspace in Toronto, making it limited to commercial flights only while all others would be restricted within a {{convert|30|nmi|km|0|adj=on}} radius.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.guelphmercury.com/News/article/650743 |title=GuelphMercury.com <U+2013> News <U+2013> Guelph pilots face G20 security restrictions |publisher=News.guelphmercury.com |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref> [[Porter Airlines]] was given permission to continue flights in and out of [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/blog-local-view/business-as-usual-for-porter/article1557544/ |title=Business as usual for Porter? |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date=2010-05-05 |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> The [[Toronto District School Board]] and [[Toronto Catholic District School Board]] cancelled school bus services to six Downtown schools on June 25,<ref>{{cite news|author=The Canadian Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/toronto/story/2010/06/18/toronto-g20-school-buses.html |title=CBC News <U+2013> Toronto <U+2013> G20 forces Toronto school bus cancellations |publisher=Cbc.ca |date= 2010-06-18|accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> affecting 45,000 students, 10,000 of whom were physically disabled.<ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/g20-notebook-police-rehearsing-crowd-control/article1610290/ |title=G20 notebook: Police rehearsing crowd control |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref>

A media centre for international media personnel, journalists, and press reporters was set up at the Direct Energy Centre at the [[Exhibition Place]] during the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g20.gc.ca/for-media/media-centre/ |title=G-20 Toronto Summit &#124; Le Sommet du G-20 <U+00E0> Toronto <U+00BB> Media Centre |publisher=G20.gc.ca |date=2010-04-28 |accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref> A {{convert|20000|sqft|m2|0|adj=on}} pavilion, called ''Experience Canada'' or ''Canadian Corridor'', was set up in the media centre to promote Canadian tourism internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ottawa.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100613/g8-g20-costs-100613/20100613/?hub=OttawaHome |title=CTV Ottawa- G8/G20 organizer says marketing Canada worth cost <U+2013> CTV News |publisher=Ottawa.ctv.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> The pavilion included three life-sized government-funded displays: ''Cityscape'', which showcased successful Canadian businesses and innovation; ''The Bridge'', which included information kiosks for media personnel as well as large high-definition screens that televised the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] games; and ''Northern Ontario Oasis'', an artificial lakefront based on [[District Municipality of Muskoka|Muskoka region's]] [[cottage country]].<ref>[http://g8.gc.ca/for-media/experience-canada/ Muskoka 2010 G-8 | Le Sommet du G-8 de 2010 <U+00E0> Muskoka<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/g8-g20/news/ottawa-steered-clear-of-corporate-sponsorships-for-g8-g20/article1608401/ |title=Ottawa steered clear of corporate sponsorships for G8-G20 |publisher=The Globe and Mail |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> The ''Northern Ontario Oasis'' included donated canoes, a shoreline with deck chairs for journalists to cool off, and a [[mobile phone]] recharging station.<ref name="thestar3">{{cite news|author=Heather Scoffield The Canadian Press |url=http://www.thestar.com/news/world/g8/article/820057--fake-lake-part-of-1-9m-g20-g8-toronto-media-centre?bn=1 |title=Fake lake part of $1.9M G20/G8 Toronto media centre |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-06-07 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> The background was a large screen that portrayed various images of the Muskoka region.<ref name=thestar3 /> The cost of the international media centre, the ''Experience Canada'' pavilion, and artificial lake, which were {{Nowrap|$23 million}}, {{Nowrap|$1.9 million}}, and $57,000 respectively, was the target of [[#Controversies|controversies]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/06/08/g20-fakelake-costs.html |title=CBC News <U+2013> Canada <U+2013> PM defends G8 fake lake pavilion |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=2010-06-08 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref>

== Attendance ==
Participants of the Toronto summit were announced by [[Stephen Harper]] on May 8, 2010. Harper extended invitations to the leaders of [[Ethiopia]] and [[Malawi]] to further represent the continent of Africa along with [[South Africa]], a G-20 member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsudanvision.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2127:canadian-prime-minister-invites-malawi-ethiopia-for-g20-summit-in-toronto&catid=3:international&Itemid=10 |title=Canadian Prime Minister invites Malawi, Ethiopia, for G20 summit in Toronto |publisher=''New Sudan Vision'' (Sudan)|date= May 5, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28}}</ref>
[[Netherlands]], [[Spain]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Nigeria]] were also invited.<ref name=punchng1>{{cite web|url=http://www.punchng.com/Articl.aspx?theartic=Art20100602522784|title=Canada invites Nigeria to G20 summit|publisher=''Punch'' (Nigeria)|date= June 2, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 }}</ref>

[[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] was the [[port of entry]] for delegates attending both the G8 and G-20 summits. French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] and Chinese president [[Hu Jintao]] were the first of the G-20 leaders to arrive. The arrival of Hu coincided with his [[state visit]] to Canada, hosted by [[Governor General of Canada]] [[Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref>Zhang Xiang. {{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/china/2010-06/17/c_13354870.htm |title=Chinese president to visit Canada, attend G20 summit |publisher=Xinhua (China) |date= June 17, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 }}; Delacourt, Susan. {{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827903 |title=Hu visit sign of 'enduring friendship,' Jean says |publisher=''Toronto Star'' (Canada) |date= June 25, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 | first=Susan | last=Delacourt}}</ref> Presidents [[Jacob Zuma]] of South Africa and [[Goodluck Jonathan]] of Nigeria arrived on June 24.<ref name="leaders_begin">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827910--leaders-begin-arriving-for-g8-g20?bn=1 |title=Leaders begin arriving for G8, G20 |publisher=''Toronto Star'' (Canada) |date= June 24, 2010 |accessdate= 2010-09-28}}</ref> David Cameron arrived on June 25, following a short visit in [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] to celebrate the centennial of the [[Canadian Forces Maritime Command]]. Remaining leaders with the G8 also arrived on the same day.<ref name=toronto2 />

The [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and the [[International Labour Organization]], as well as Ethiopia, Malawi, Nigeria, and Vietnam made their first G-20 summit attendances in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?category=1&id=3342 |title=Prime Minister of Canada: PM announces participation of key leaders at the Toronto G-20 Summit this June|publisher=Prime Minister's official website (Canada) |date= May 8, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28}}; Moulid, Hussein. {{cite web|url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7018646957 |title=Ethiopia<U+0092>s Zenawi, Four Other Leaders Invited To Join G20 Toronto Summit|publisher=All Headline News (US) |date= May 10, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 }}</ref> Recently designated heads of government, namely [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British prime minister]] [[David Cameron]] and [[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese prime minister]] [[Naoto Kan]], made the [[36th G8 summit|G8]] and G-20 summits their first international [[diplomatic conference|conferences]].<ref name="toronto2">{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100624/g8-g20-leaders-arrive-100624/20100624/?hub=TorontoNewHome |title=Leaders arrive in Canada ahead of G8/G20 summits |publisher=CTV (Canada) |date= June 24, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 }}</ref> Australia's deputy prime minister, [[Wayne Swan]], attended the summit on behalf of [[Julia Gillard]], whose appointment as prime minister happened on June 24.<ref name="toronto2" /> [[Brazil]]ian [[President of Brazil|president]] [[Luiz In<U+00E1>cio Lula da Silva]] cancelled his trip to stay back and monitor the situation on [[2010 northeastern Brazil floods|the recent flooding in northeastern Brazil]]; in his place, [[Guido Mantega]], Brazil's finance minister, headed the nation's delegation.<ref>Dantas, Iuri. {{cite web|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-25/lula-will-skip-g-20-summit-to-oversee-brazil-flood-relief-official-says.html |title=Lula Will Skip G-20 Summit to Oversee Brazil Flood Relief, Official Says |publisher=Bloomberg (US) |date= June 25, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28}}</ref> After the G8 summit in [[Huntsville, Ontario]] ended, Cameron, whose aircraft was grounded due to weather conditions, shared transportation to Toronto in [[Marine One]] with the [[President of the United States|United States' president]], [[Barack Obama]].<ref>Wardell, Jane {{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2010/06/28/britains_cameron_bolsters_reputation_at_summits/ |title=Britain's Cameron bolsters reputation at summits |publisher=''Boston Globe'' (US) |date= June 28, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-28 | first=Jane | last=Wardell}}</ref>

